Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England","Barforth, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1278–1342":"1278–1342","1272–1308":"1272–1308","1303–Male":"1303–Deceased","1308–1365":"1308–1365","1250–1278":"1250–1278","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","before 1278":"before 1278","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","about 1308":"about 1308","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1365":"1365","1342":"1342","1308":"1308","after 1278":"after 1278","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Barforth, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Barford, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England","Barforth, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Barforth Hall, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pudsey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pudsey (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Podechesai(e)</i> in 1086,  <i>Pudekesseya</i> in the 12th century, and  <i>Pudekeshay</i> in 1219. The place-name probably derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pudoc</i> (genitive * <i>Pudoces</i>) + Old English  <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Pudsey stands on the top of a hill, and so in this case  <i>ēg</i> may have the sense ‘hill spur, island of good land in moorland’. Alternatively, the final element may be Old English  <i>(ge)hæg</i> ‘enclosure’ or  <i>hēah</i> ‘high ground, height’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sor